<li id="cite_note-39"><b><a href="#cite_ref-39" title="">^</a></b> In Wagner's era, horns (the word "French horn" is now obsolete) were tuned and could play only in a single key, so they were called "single horns". Wagner scored <i>Das Rheingold</i> for eight single horns: four "high horns", which are B-flat single horns, and four "low horns", F-natural single horns. Wagner specified that the players of two F-natural, high, single horns, identified as Horn Nos. 5 and 7, double on the tenor Wagner tubas, and that the players of two B-flat, low, single horns, identified as Horn Nos. 6 and 8, double on the bass Wagner tubas. In 1897, the double horn was invented, which played in both B-flat and F-natural, thus obviating the need for players to use separately-tuned horns.</li>
